1
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:03,500
SECTION 1

2
00:00:03,500 --> 00:00:07,700
- Hello, South City Cycling Club.
- Oh, hi.

3
00:00:08,700 --> 00:00:13,606
Um, I want to find out
about joining the club.

4
00:00:13,606 --> 00:00:16,056
Right, I can help you there.

5
00:00:16,056 --> 00:00:19,986
I'm the club secretary, and my name's Jim Hunter.

6
00:00:20,056 --> 00:00:24,676
- Oh, hi Jim.
- So, are you interested in membership for yourself?

7
00:00:24,676 --> 00:00:26,676
- That's right.
- Okay.

8
00:00:27,208 --> 00:00:30,708
Well, there are basically two types of adult membership.

9
00:00:30,708 --> 00:00:35,906
If you're pretty serious about cycling, there's the full membership.

10
00:00:35,906 --> 00:00:40,544
That costs $260, and that covers you,

11
00:00:40,544 --> 00:00:45,004
not just for ordinary cycling, but also for races,

12
00:00:45,004 --> 00:00:49,744
both here in the city and also in other parts of Australia.

13
00:00:49,744 --> 00:00:52,467
- Right. Well, I'm not really up to that standard.
- Okay.

14
00:00:53,157 --> 00:00:57,554
I was more interested in just joining a group to do some cycling in my free time.

15
00:00:57,554 --> 00:01:01,054
- Sure, that's why most people join.
- Yeah.

16
00:01:01,054 --> 00:01:06,198
So, in that case, you'd be better with the recreational membership.

17
00:01:06,198 --> 00:01:10,444
That's $108 if you're over 19,

18
00:01:10,445 --> 00:01:13,388
and $95 if you're under.

19
00:01:13,387 --> 00:01:15,910
- I'm 25.
- Okay.

20
00:01:15,910 --> 00:01:18,910
It's paid quarterly, and you can upgrade it later

21
00:01:18,910 --> 00:01:22,410
to the full membership if you want to, of course.

22
00:01:22,410 --> 00:01:27,410
Now, both types of membership include the club fee of $20.

23
00:01:27,410 --> 00:01:31,910
They also provide insurance in case you have an accident,

24
00:01:31,910 --> 00:01:35,410
though we hope you won't need that, of course.

25
00:01:35,410 --> 00:01:39,910
- No. Okay. Well, I'll go with the recreational membership, I think.
- Right.

26
00:01:39,910 --> 00:01:44,410
- And that allows me to join in the club activities and so on?
- That's right.

27
00:01:44,410 --> 00:01:47,910
And once you're a member of the club, you're also permitted

28
00:01:47,910 --> 00:01:51,910
to wear our kit when you're out cycling. It's green and white.

29
00:01:51,910 --> 00:01:56,410
- Yes, I've seen cyclists wearing it. So can I buy that at the club?
- Ah, no.

30
00:01:56,410 --> 00:02:00,910
It's made to order by a company in Brisbane. You can find them online.

31
00:02:00,910 --> 00:02:06,910
They're called Jerry's. That's J-E-R-R-I-Z.

32
00:02:06,910 --> 00:02:10,910
You can use your membership number to put in an order on their website.

33
00:02:10,910 --> 00:02:13,910
- Okay. Now can you tell me a bit about the rides I can do?
- Sure.

34
00:02:13,910 --> 00:02:18,910
So, we have training rides pretty well every morning, and they're a really good way

35
00:02:18,910 --> 00:02:23,910
of improving your cycling skills as well as your general level of fitness,

36
00:02:23,910 --> 00:02:26,410
but they're different levels.

37
00:02:26,410 --> 00:02:30,910
Level A is pretty fast. You're looking at about 30 or 35 kilometers an hour.

38
00:02:30,910 --> 00:02:36,410
If you can do about 25 kilometers an hour, you'd probably be Level B.

39
00:02:36,410 --> 00:02:41,410
And then Level C are the novices who stay at about 15 kilometers per hour.

40
00:02:41,410 --> 00:02:46,410
- Right. Well, I reckon I'd be Level B. So when are the sessions for that level?
- Uh...

41
00:02:46,410 --> 00:02:51,410
There are a couple each week. They're both early morning sessions.

42
00:02:51,410 --> 00:02:54,910
There's one on Tuesdays, and for that one, you meet at 5:30 AM,

43
00:02:54,910 --> 00:02:58,410
and the meeting point's the stadium. Do you know where that is?

44
00:02:58,410 --> 00:03:02,910
- Yes, it's quite near my home, in fact. Okay, and how about the other one?
- Right.

45
00:03:02,910 --> 00:03:07,910
That's on Thursdays. It starts at the same time, but they meet at the main gate to the park.

46
00:03:07,910 --> 00:03:11,910
- Is that the one just past the shopping mall?
- That's it.

47
00:03:14,910 --> 00:03:18,910
- So, how long are the rides?
- Ah, they're about an hour and a half.

48
00:03:18,910 --> 00:03:22,910
So, if you have a job, it's easy to fit in before you go to work.

49
00:03:22,910 --> 00:03:27,410
And the members often go somewhere for coffee afterwards, so it's quite a social event.

50
00:03:27,410 --> 00:03:31,410
- Okay, that sounds good. I've only just moved to the city, so I don't actually know many people yet.
- Right.

51
00:03:31,410 --> 00:03:35,410
- Well, it's a great way to meet people.
- And does each ride have a leader?

52
00:03:35,410 --> 00:03:39,910
- Sometimes, but not always, but you don't really need one.
- Okay.

53
00:03:39,910 --> 00:03:43,910
The group members on the rides support one another anyway.

54
00:03:43,910 --> 00:03:47,410
- How would we know where to go?
- If you check the club website,

55
00:03:47,410 --> 00:03:51,410
you'll see that the route for each ride is clearly marked.

56
00:03:51,410 --> 00:03:54,910
So, you can just print that out and take it along with you.

57
00:03:54,910 --> 00:04:00,410
It's similar from one week to another, but it's not always exactly the same.

58
00:04:00,410 --> 00:04:03,910
- And what do I need to bring?
- Hmm, well, bring a bottle of water

59
00:04:03,910 --> 00:04:07,910
and your phone. You shouldn't use it while you're cycling, but have it with you.

60
00:04:07,910 --> 00:04:10,410
- Right.
- And in winter,

61
00:04:10,410 --> 00:04:14,410
it's well before sunrise when we set out, so you need to make sure your bike's got lights.

62
00:04:14,410 --> 00:04:18,910
- That's okay. Well, thanks, Jim. I'd definitely like to join.
- Great.

63
00:04:18,910 --> 00:04:22,910
- So what's the best way of going about it?
- Ah, you can...

64
00:04:22,910 --> 00:04:28,910
SECTION 2

65
00:04:28,910 --> 00:04:32,910
Thanks for coming, everyone. Okay, so this meeting is for new staff

66
00:04:32,910 --> 00:04:37,410
and staff who haven't been involved with our volunteering projects yet.

67
00:04:37,410 --> 00:04:41,910
So, basically, the idea is that we allow staff to give up some of their work time

68
00:04:41,910 --> 00:04:46,410
to help on various charity projects to benefit the local community.

69
00:04:46,410 --> 00:04:51,410
We've been doing this for the last five years, and it's been very successful.

70
00:04:51,410 --> 00:04:56,410
Participating doesn't necessarily involve a huge time commitment.

71
00:04:56,410 --> 00:05:00,910
The company will pay for eight hours of your time.

72
00:05:00,910 --> 00:05:05,910
That can be used over one or two days, all at once,

73
00:05:05,910 --> 00:05:10,410
or spread over several months throughout the year.

74
00:05:10,410 --> 00:05:14,410
There are some staff who enjoy volunteering so much,

75
00:05:14,410 --> 00:05:19,410
they also give up their own free time for a couple of hours every week.

76
00:05:19,410 --> 00:05:23,910
It's completely up to you. Obviously, many people will have family commitments

77
00:05:23,910 --> 00:05:27,910
and aren't as available as other members of staff.

78
00:05:27,910 --> 00:05:32,410
Feedback from staff has been overwhelmingly positive,

79
00:05:32,410 --> 00:05:35,910
because they felt they were doing something really useful.

80
00:05:35,910 --> 00:05:40,910
Nearly everyone agreed that volunteering made them feel more motivated at work.

81
00:05:40,910 --> 00:05:45,410
They also liked building relationships with the people in the local community

82
00:05:45,410 --> 00:05:49,410
and felt valued by them. One or two people also said

83
00:05:49,410 --> 00:05:53,410
it was a good thing to have on their CVs.

84
00:05:53,410 --> 00:05:58,410
One particularly successful project last year was the "Get Working" project.

85
00:05:58,410 --> 00:06:02,910
This was aimed at helping unemployed people in the area get back to work.

86
00:06:02,910 --> 00:06:07,910
Our staff were able to help them improve their telephone skills,

87
00:06:07,910 --> 00:06:12,410
such as writing down messages and speaking with confidence to potential customers,

88
00:06:12,410 --> 00:06:16,410
which they had found quite difficult.

89
00:06:16,410 --> 00:06:20,410
This is something many employers look for in job applicants,

90
00:06:20,410 --> 00:06:24,910
and something we all do without even thinking about every day at work.

91
00:06:24,910 --> 00:06:29,410
We've got an exciting new project starting this year.

92
00:06:29,410 --> 00:06:33,910
Up until now, we've mainly focused on projects to do with education and training,

93
00:06:33,910 --> 00:06:38,410
and we'll continue with our reading project in schools and our work with local charities.

94
00:06:38,410 --> 00:06:43,410
But we've also agreed to help out on a conservation project

95
00:06:43,410 --> 00:06:47,910
in Redfern Park. So if any of you fancy being outside

96
00:06:47,910 --> 00:06:51,910
and getting your hands dirty, this is the project for you.

97
00:06:51,910 --> 00:06:56,410
I also wanted to mention the annual Digital Inclusion Day,

98
00:06:56,410 --> 00:06:59,910
which is coming up next month.

99
00:06:59,910 --> 00:07:03,910
The aim of this is to help older people keep up with technology.

100
00:07:03,910 --> 00:07:07,910
And this year, instead of hosting the event in our own training facility,

101
00:07:07,910 --> 00:07:13,410
we're using the ICT suite at Hill College, as it can hold far more people.

102
00:07:13,410 --> 00:07:17,910
We've invited over 60 people from the Silver Age Community Center to take part,

103
00:07:17,910 --> 00:07:22,410
so we'll need a lot of volunteers to help with this event.

104
00:07:22,410 --> 00:07:26,410
If you're interested in taking part, please go to the volunteering section of our website

105
00:07:26,410 --> 00:07:30,910
and complete the relevant form. We won't be providing any training for this,

106
00:07:30,910 --> 00:07:35,410
but you'll be paired with an experienced volunteer if you've never done it before.

107
00:07:35,410 --> 00:07:39,910
By the way, don't forget to tell your manager about any volunteering activities

108
00:07:39,910 --> 00:07:43,410
you decide to do.

109
00:07:43,410 --> 00:07:47,910
The participants on the Digital Inclusion Day really benefited.

110
00:07:47,910 --> 00:07:52,910
The majority were in their 70s, though some were younger, and a few were even in their 90s.

111
00:07:52,910 --> 00:07:57,910
Quite a few owned both a computer and a mobile phone,

112
00:07:57,910 --> 00:08:01,910
but these tended to be outdated models.

113
00:08:01,910 --> 00:08:05,910
They generally knew how to do simple things like send texts,

114
00:08:05,910 --> 00:08:10,910
but weren't aware of recent developments in mobile phone technology.

115
00:08:10,910 --> 00:08:15,410
A few were keen to learn, but most were quite dismissive at first.

116
00:08:15,410 --> 00:08:19,910
They couldn't see the point of updating their skills, but that soon changed.

117
00:08:19,910 --> 00:08:24,410
The feedback was very positive. The really encouraging thing was

118
00:08:24,410 --> 00:08:29,410
that participants all said they felt much more confident about using social media

119
00:08:29,410 --> 00:08:33,910
to keep in touch with their grandchildren, who prefer this form of communication

120
00:08:33,910 --> 00:08:37,910
to phoning or sending emails.

121
00:08:37,910 --> 00:08:42,410
A lot of them also said playing online games would help them make new friends

122
00:08:42,410 --> 00:08:46,410
and keep their brains active.

123
00:08:46,410 --> 00:08:51,410
They weren't that impressed with being able to order their groceries online,

124
00:08:51,410 --> 00:08:55,410
as they liked going out to the shops, but some said

125
00:08:55,410 --> 00:08:59,910
it would come in handy if they were ill or the weather was really bad.

126
00:08:59,910 --> 00:09:03,910
One thing they asked about was using tablets for things like reading newspapers.

127
00:09:03,910 --> 00:09:08,910
Some people had been given tablets as presents but had never used them.

128
00:09:08,910 --> 00:09:13,910
So that's something we'll make sure we include this time.

129
00:09:13,910 --> 00:09:18,910
SECTION 3

130
00:09:18,910 --> 00:09:22,410
- Ah, come in, Russ.
- Thank you.

131
00:09:22,410 --> 00:09:25,410
- Now, you wanted to consult me about your class presentation on nanotechnology.
- Yes.

132
00:09:25,410 --> 00:09:28,910
- You're due to give it next week, aren't you?
- That's right, and I'm really struggling.

133
00:09:28,910 --> 00:09:32,910
I chose the topic because I didn't know much about it and wanted to learn more.

134
00:09:32,910 --> 00:09:36,910
But now I've read so much about it, in a way, there's too much to say.

135
00:09:36,910 --> 00:09:40,910
I could talk for much longer than the 20 minutes I've been allocated.

136
00:09:40,910 --> 00:09:44,910
Should I assume the other students don't know much and give them a kind of general introduction?

137
00:09:44,910 --> 00:09:49,910
Or should I try and make them share my fascination with a particular aspect?

138
00:09:49,910 --> 00:09:53,910
- You could do either, but you'll need to have it clear in your own mind.
- Right.

139
00:09:53,910 --> 00:09:56,910
- Then I think I'll give an overview.
- Okay.

140
00:09:56,910 --> 00:10:01,410
Now, one way of approaching this is to work through developments in chronological order.

141
00:10:01,410 --> 00:10:03,410
- Uh-huh.
- On the other hand,

142
00:10:03,410 --> 00:10:06,910
you could talk about the numerous ways that nanotechnology is being applied.

143
00:10:06,910 --> 00:10:10,910
- You mean things like thin films on camera displays to make them water-repellent?
- Yes.

144
00:10:10,910 --> 00:10:15,410
- And additives to make motorcycle helmets stronger and lighter?
- Exactly.

145
00:10:15,410 --> 00:10:20,410
Or another way would be to focus on its impact in one particular area,

146
00:10:20,410 --> 00:10:23,910
say medicine or space exploration.

147
00:10:23,910 --> 00:10:27,910
- That would make it easier to focus. Perhaps I should do that?
- Right.

148
00:10:27,910 --> 00:10:32,410
- I think that would be a good idea.
- Right. How important is it to include slides in the presentation?

149
00:10:32,410 --> 00:10:36,410
They aren't essential by any means. And there's a danger of tailoring

150
00:10:36,410 --> 00:10:39,910
what you say to fit whatever slides you can find.

151
00:10:39,910 --> 00:10:44,410
While it can be good to include slides, you could end up spending too long looking for suitable ones.

152
00:10:44,410 --> 00:10:47,910
You might find it better to leave them out.

153
00:10:47,910 --> 00:10:51,910
- I see. Another thing I was wondering about was how to start.
- Yeah.

154
00:10:51,910 --> 00:10:55,910
I know presentations often begin with "First I'm going to talk about this,

155
00:10:55,910 --> 00:10:59,410
and then I'll talk about that." But I thought about asking the audience

156
00:10:59,410 --> 00:11:02,910
what they know about nanotechnology.

157
00:11:02,910 --> 00:11:06,910
That would be fine if you had an hour or two for the presentation.

158
00:11:06,910 --> 00:11:11,410
But you might find that you can't do anything with the answers you get,

159
00:11:11,410 --> 00:11:14,910
and it simply eats into the short time that's available.

160
00:11:14,910 --> 00:11:19,410
- So maybe I should mention a particular way that nanotechnology is used, to focus people's attention?
- Yes.

161
00:11:19,410 --> 00:11:22,410
- That sounds sensible.
- What do you think I should do next?

162
00:11:22,410 --> 00:11:25,910
I really have to plan the presentation today and tomorrow.

163
00:11:25,910 --> 00:11:30,410
Well, initially, I think you should ignore all the notes you've made,

164
00:11:30,410 --> 00:11:34,910
take a small piece of paper, and write a single short sentence

165
00:11:34,910 --> 00:11:38,410
that ties together the whole presentation.

166
00:11:38,410 --> 00:11:43,410
It can be something as simple as "Nanotechnology is already improving our lives."

167
00:11:43,410 --> 00:11:47,410
Then start planning the content around that.

168
00:11:47,410 --> 00:11:51,410
You can always modify that sentence later if you need to.

169
00:11:51,410 --> 00:11:53,910
- Okay.
- Right.

170
00:11:53,910 --> 00:11:57,910
Okay, now let's think about actually giving the presentation.

171
00:11:57,910 --> 00:12:02,410
You've only given one before, if I remember correctly, about an experiment you'd been involved in.

172
00:12:02,410 --> 00:12:05,910
- That's right. It was pretty rubbish.
- Well...

173
00:12:05,910 --> 00:12:09,910
Let's say it was better in some respects than in others.

174
00:12:09,910 --> 00:12:14,410
With regard to the structure, I felt that you ended rather abruptly,

175
00:12:14,410 --> 00:12:17,410
without rounding it off.

176
00:12:17,410 --> 00:12:21,410
Be careful not to do that in next week's presentation.

177
00:12:21,410 --> 00:12:24,410
- Okay.
- And you made very little eye contact

178
00:12:24,410 --> 00:12:28,410
with the audience because you were looking down at your notes most of the time.

179
00:12:28,410 --> 00:12:32,910
You need to be looking at the audience, and only occasionally glancing at your notes.

180
00:12:32,910 --> 00:12:36,410
- Hm.
- Your body language was a little odd.

181
00:12:36,410 --> 00:12:40,910
Every time you showed a slide, you turned your back on the audience so you could look at it.

182
00:12:40,910 --> 00:12:44,910
You should have been looking at your laptop.

183
00:12:44,910 --> 00:12:49,410
And you kept scratching your head, so I found myself wondering when you were next going to do that,

184
00:12:49,410 --> 00:12:53,410
instead of listening to what you were saying.

185
00:12:53,410 --> 00:12:57,410
- Oh, dear. What did you think of the language?
- Right.

186
00:12:57,410 --> 00:13:01,910
- I knew that not everyone was familiar with the subject, so I tried to make it as simple as I could.
- Yes.

187
00:13:01,910 --> 00:13:04,910
That came across. You used a few words that are specific to the field,

188
00:13:04,910 --> 00:13:09,910
but you always explained what they meant, so the audience wouldn't have had any difficulty understanding.

189
00:13:09,910 --> 00:13:12,410
- Uh-huh.
- I must say,

190
00:13:12,410 --> 00:13:16,410
the handouts you prepared were well thought out. They were a good summary of your presentation,

191
00:13:16,410 --> 00:13:20,910
which people would have been able to refer to later on. So, well done on that.

192
00:13:20,910 --> 00:13:24,910
- Thank you.
- Well, I hope that helps you with next week's presentation.

193
00:13:24,910 --> 00:13:28,910
- Yes, it will. Thanks a lot.
- I'll look forward to seeing a big improvement then.

